    "summary": "Archimedes of Syracuse (c. 287–212 BC) was the greatest mathematician and engineer of antiquity, combining theoretical mathematical genius with practical inventive brilliance in a way unmatched until Leonardo da Vinci. His mathematical works established the value of pi to unprecedented precision, calculated the surface area and volume of a sphere, developed methods for calculating areas under curves (anticipating integral calculus by 1,800 years), and explored the mathematics of very large numbers in the Sand Reckoner.\n\nHis practical inventions and engineering achievements were equally remarkable: the Archimedes screw (a helical device for raising water, still used today), compound pulleys and levers ('give me a place to stand and I can move the world'), war machines for the defense of Syracuse including catapults and cranes that lifted and capsized Roman ships — described in astonished terms by ancient historians who laid siege to the city. His principle of buoyancy (Archimedes' Principle) — that a body submerged in fluid experiences an upward force equal to the weight of displaced fluid — reputedly discovered while stepping into a bath, prompting the legendary cry 'Eureka!' — remains fundamental to fluid mechanics. He was killed by a Roman soldier during the [[event:3817|Siege of Syracuse]] despite Roman general Marcellus's orders to take him alive.",
